postcontent:
Large tri-color Point Blank intercepter with throat protection, yoke, collar outer shell and two level three 10x12 multi hit Strike Face sapi plates.

The Interceptor body armor system consists of an Outer Tactical Vest (OTV) and two Small Arms Protective Inserts (SAPI). The OTV is lined with finely woven Kevlar aramid, these two parts of the vest are both bullet and heat resistant. The vest was tested to stop a 9 mm 124 GR full metal jacket bullet (FMJ) at 1,400 ft/s (426 m/s) with minimal deformation and has a V-50 of roughly 1,525 ft/s (465 m/s). This means that the bullet has to be traveling faster than 1,525 ft/s for it to have more than a 50% chance of breaking through the armor panel. 

The vest proved its protection prowess in Afghanistan and Iraq in which many U.S. soldiers were saved by wearing them[citation needed]. In particular, it is credited with saving the lives of 29 American servicemen in Afghanistan. There were delays in equipping the entire force with the Interceptor vest at the beginning of this war.

The Interceptor system weighs a total of 16.4 pounds. (7.4 kg)
Vest weighing 8.4 pounds. (3.8 kg)
Plates inserted weighing four pounds (1.8 kg) each.

In 1980, Taurus purchased the Beretta factory in Sao Paulo, Brazil "lock, stock and barrel" and immediately sought to improve on the Beretta design, resulting in the popular and acclaimed Taurus 92. Always looking to raise the bar, we've taken this year's models a step further than they've ever been. Most notable is Taurus' specially designed drop hammer forged ordnance grade alloy frame that won't crack or allow the slide to come off. Other innovations include a three-position frame-mounted ambidextrous safety, which is more secure than a slide mounted safety, and allows for a classic SA "cocked-and-locked" mode, as well as functioning as a DA decocking lever. Available in fixed sight model 92 you'll be able to face any situation without compromise.


 	Loaded Chamber Indicator
Taurus provides a loaded chamber indicator on all new compact, medium and large frame pistols. As with all Taurus safety and security innovations, the indicator in no way interferes with the operation of your pistol and is provided at no extra cost, but gives you an "at-a-glance" verification that there is a round in the chamber. When a round is in the chamber, the ejector pops out of the slide, exposing a red strip just behind the ejection port. While any loaded chamber indicator is no substitute for common sense and safe firearm handling, it is one more example of Taurus' commitment to outstanding firearms.
	3 Position Safety Decocker
Try the ambidextrous Three-Position Safety on any Taurus pistol capable of firing in both single action and double action. It's easily operated and provided at no additional charge. Depress with your thumb and safely drop the hammer to de-cock the pistol. The safety returns to the OFF position, ready for double action shooting. Push the safety up and your cocked pistol is safe to carry in the single action mode. When applied to a de-cocked pistol, safety is ON and the first shot is double action.
 	Taurus Security System (TSS)a
All the Taurus family of revolvers features the Taurus Security System, which provides instant-ready defense with built-in ability to secure your firearm and make it inoperable at the turn of a key. When the Security System is engaged, the pistol cannot be fired or cocked and the gun's manual safety cannot be disengaged. As with our revolver Security System, the device is part of the firearm and cannot be lost, and the same special Security Key works for both the revolver and pistol Systems (two keys come with each gun). To engage: simply insert the Key into the button on the rear or side of the pistol and rotate one-quarter turn clockwise. This engages the Security System. The manual safety cannot be moved and the trigger cannot be pulled. To disengage: simply rotate the key one-quarter turn back. This releases the Security System, yet leaves the pistol's manual safety in the "safe" position until you are ready to release it yourself and fire the gun.

title: For Sale:  COLT 1877 "LIGHTNING" .38
postcontent: Manufactured in 1882, requires NO FFL, since it qualifies as a pre-1898 antique. Can be shipped to your home. This is a Colt Model 1877 double action, single action revolver, "Lightning" with a 3.5 inch barrel. The rifling is still visible, at least all the lands and grooves are there. The original nickel finish is gone, only showing a hint here and there of nickel in some places. Much of the original "COLTS PT.F.A.MFG. Co./HARTFORD CT U.S.A.," and Colt leaping horse with patent date stamping on the top of the barrel and left side on the frame is worn away. What shows is..."..TS PT.F.A.MFG. Co./..RTFORD CT U.S.A.".. the address on the top of the barrel is mostly there. The serial number is found on the trigger guard, and frame #38085, in parts on the handle. The Colt factory assembly numbers stamped with #58, within the pistol match, so the trigger and frame, loading gate are consistent, all matching parts to the pistol. The grips fit nice, as they are replacement reproductions to the Colt. The original brass stanchions and screw were taken from the original grips and installed into the new grips. The action functions in double action only, but the cylinder does not advance. The cylinder moves freely by hand, and does not seem to engage the bolt, as the bolt is worn. The trigger spring needs to be replaced, and so trigger does not return fully without manually resetting. The hammer does not work in single action, nor will it stay in the cocked or half cock positions. All internal parts are there. This pistol is a good collectible, "non-shooter," antique Colt 1877 Lightning in .38 long Colt cal. manufactured in 1882.  http://www.coltparts.com/pt_1877da.html

title: For Sale/Trade:  Bear Encounter RH Compound Bow
postcontent:
This bow includes Trophy Ridge sights, rest and quiver. There is also a True Fire release and 4 arrows. 60# draw weight, adjustable down to 50#.

I decided to try hunting with a compound bow---I am a complete novice. My nephew is an accomplished archer and bow hunter. He recommended the Bear Encounter as being better than most of the quality entry level bows. There are numerous articles & reviews on the web that give this bow really high marks for what it is, which is apparently an entry level to mid-level bow. There were two used ones on ebay that looked like a good buy, ending about the same time. Not intending to, I ended up buying both. The one I am keeping looks new, literally. My nephew says this one is in VG to excellent condition, but he thinks the string is going to need replacing next season. The arrows appear to be in fine condition; the broadheads are so-so. Owners Manual is available online at the Bear website; it includes directions to adjust draw length or weight. I will try to answer any questions, but please remember I am new to this....I am relying on my nephew's knowledge.

Arrow rest is a fall way, appears to be Trophy Ridge Revolution from pictures I've found online. Sight appears to be a Trophy Ridge Sharpshooter (again my best guess looking at pictures online). My nephew thought it was a great package for the $$ when I bought it, but having two I am now looking to get back what I paid for this one. Price may have a little room for negotiation, but I would negotiate only in person....you can't really make me a legitimate offer unless you're in front of me with money in hand.
